International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Thu, 10 Feb 2005 14:37:17 +1100
From: Raina MacIntyre <RainaM@chw.edu.au>
Does anyone know anything about the following press report in the Sri
Lankan media? Could this be something tsunami-related?
Raina MacIntyre
National Centre for Immunisation Research
Children's Hospital at Westmead and University of Sydney
Westmead, NSW
Australia, 2145
[This article was not identified by origin of news source, but a
similar article was found at:
<http://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/Display_news.asp?section=world_news&month=february2005&file=world_news2005021085740.xml>
- Mod.MPP]

Mystery heart disease worries docs
Emergency meeting of medical bigwigs
-----------------------
A fever that affects the human heart is prevalent in some parts of
the country, and medical specialists have expressed grave concern
over the inability of the health authorities to identify what really
causes it.
In Badulla, over 70 persons have contracted this fever, Senior
Cardiologist Dr. Anindu Pathirana of the Badulla General Hospital
told The Island. He said the patients had breathing difficulties,
severe chest pain and dizziness as symptoms.
Palpitation was also common among the patients, he said. Over 50
percent of them had a history of the undiagnosed fever.
Dr. Pathirana said it was the 1st time that he had come across the
disease. It took months for patients to recover and in some cases
death could result due to heart failure if early treatment was not
sought, he said, adding that there was however no need for the public
to panic.
He said the majority of the patients were above 12 years -- mostly
young adults. Doctors suspect a viral infection to be the cause of
this condition, but there was no conclusive proof, Dr. Pathirana
said. 2 doctors had also contracted the disease, he said.
He said the hospital had sent blood samples to the Medical Research
Institute (MRI) for investigations but it had not received reports.
Dr. Mrs. Geethani Wickremesinghe of the MRI, contacted for her
comments, said they had not received any such samples. She referred
The Island to the Epidemiology Unit of the Health Ministry.
Chief Epidemiologist Dr. Nihal Abeysinghe said his institution was
aware of the disease and an emergency meeting of medical experts
including cardiologists and virologists had been called tomorrow to
conduct investigations.
[Byline: Dasun Edirisinghe]
--
Associate Professor C Raina MacIntyre
